<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,513,539]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Melichar" box="[668,759,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Calodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca">
<emphasis box="[668,759,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the structure of the male genitalia but can be easily distinguished by the presence of numerous long spines in the distal ¾ of the proximal process of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1328,1427,549,575]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1962,1987]" captionTargetBox="[175,1384,197,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[165,1423,166,1943]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 19 A–H. Calodia neofusca sp. nov., male genitalia. A &amp; B. Aedeagus, dorsal view; C &amp; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Subgenital plate, dorsal view; F. Style, dorsal view; G. Connective, dorsal view; H. Pygofer, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3366582/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig.19 B</figureCitation>
) compared to only distal ½ in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Melichar" box="[478,569,585,611]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Calodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca">
<emphasis box="[478,569,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[584,690,585,611]" captionStart="FIGURES 14" captionStartId="49.[151,264,1761,1786]" captionTargetBox="[255,1330,207,1700]" captionTargetId="figure@49.[233,1354,181,1741]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURES 14 A–N. Species of Calodia, male genitalia. A–D. C. bicompressa Nielson; E–G. C. fusca (Melichar); H–K. C. paraostenta Nielson; L–N. C. propennata Nielson. Modified and reproduced from Nielson 2015 (Figs. A–D), Nielson 1982 (Figs. E–G) and Nielson 1991 (Figs. H–N)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3366572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 14 F</figureCitation>
). The subgenital plate lacks an apical spine in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meshram" authorityYear="2019" box="[1209,1341,585,611]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Calodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neofusca">
<emphasis box="[1209,1341,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. neofusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="54.[151,264,1962,1987]" captionTargetBox="[175,1384,197,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@54.[165,1423,166,1943]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURES 19 A–H. Calodia neofusca sp. nov., male genitalia. A &amp; B. Aedeagus, dorsal view; C &amp; D. Aedeagus, lateral view; E. Subgenital plate, dorsal view; F. Style, dorsal view; G. Connective, dorsal view; H. Pygofer, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3366582/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 19 E</figureCitation>
) but a spine is present in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Melichar" box="[455,547,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Calodia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca">
<emphasis box="[455,547,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
